{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-jsx","path":"/post/compact-hausdorff-space-is-normal","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>The term \"space\" in this article refers to \"topological space\".</p>\n<h1 id=\"definition\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#definition\" aria-label=\"definition permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Definition</h1>\n<h3 id=\"hausdorff-space\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#hausdorff-space\" aria-label=\"hausdorff space permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Hausdorff space</h3>\n<p>Hausdorff space is a space whoose every two points can be separated by disjoint neighborhoods. In other words:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>A space $X$ is called a Hausdorff space if every distinct points $x$, $y$ in $X$, there are neighborhood U of x and neighborhood V of y which are disjoint.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h3 id=\"normal-space\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#normal-space\" aria-label=\"normal space permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Normal space</h3>\n<p>Normal space is similar but strict than Hausdorff space:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>A space $X$ is said to be normal if every pair of disjoint closed sets $A$ and $B$, there are disjoint neighborhoods $U \\supset A$ and $V \\supset B$.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h1 id=\"theorem\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#theorem\" aria-label=\"theorem permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Theorem</h1>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Compact Hausdorff space is normal. In fact, every disjoint compact sets $A$, $B$ of a Hausdorff space, there is disjoint open sets $U \\supset A$ and $V \\supset B$.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h2 id=\"proof\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#proof\" aria-label=\"proof permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Proof</h2>\n<p>Let $X$ be a Hausdorff space and let $A, B \\subset X$ be disjoint compact subsets. Since $X$ is Hausdorff, for every pair of points $a \\in A$ and $b \\in B$, there exist disjoint open subsets, say $U<em>{ab}, V</em>{ab}$ so that $a \\in U<em>{ab}$ and $b \\in V</em>{ab}$.</p>\n<p>First, fix $a$ and consider a collection $\\mathcal{V<em>a} = \\{ V</em>{ab}\\ |\\ b \\in B\\}$. This forms an open cover for $B$, so that has a finite subcover $V<em>a$. WLOG, assume $\\mathcal{V</em>a}$ is finite.</p>\n<p>Consider corresponding open set $U<em>{a} = \\bigcap</em>{V<em>{ab} \\in \\mathcal{V</em>A}} U<em>{ab}$ (open since finite intersection). Bing $\\{ U</em>a | a \\in A \\}$ an open cover for $A$, there is a finite subcover $U$ for A.</p>\n<p>Let $V$ be the intersection of corresponding $V_a$'s. Now we have disjoin open set $U$ and $V$ containing $A$ and $B$ respectively. □</p>\n<h1 id=\"reference\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#reference\" aria-label=\"reference permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Reference</h1>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.math3ma.com/blog/compact-hausdorff-normal\">Compact + Hausdorff = Normal - Math3ma</a></li>\n</ul>","timeToRead":1,"excerpt":"The term \"space\" in this article refers to \"topological space\". Definition Hausdorff space Hausdorff space is a space whoose every two…","frontmatter":{"title":"Compact Hausdorff space is normal","cover":null,"date":"2020-06-03T17:58:05.000Z","category":null,"tags":["Math","Topology"],"latex":true},"fields":{"slug":"/compact-hausdorff-space-is-normal","date":"2020-06-03T00:00:00.000Z"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/compact-hausdorff-space-is-normal","nexttitle":"pacman 사용법","nextslug":"/pacman-사용법","prevtitle":"Setting Mac","prevslug":"/setting-mac"}},"staticQueryHashes":[]}